title: Stock Futures Slip With Earnings Season Set to Begin; Results are due from JPMorgan Chase, BlackRock and Delta Air Lines before the opening bell
text:
European stocks fell Wednesday for a two-day losing streak. The Stoxx Europe 600 was down 0.4% in morning trade dragged down by declines in healthcare and real-estate sectors.

The U.K.'s FTSE 100 was lower 0.5%. Other stock indexes in Europe also mostly slipped as France's CAC 40 shed 0.5%, the U.K.'s FTSE 250 fell 0.2% and Germany's DAX lost 0.2%.

The Swiss franc, the euro and the British pound strengthened 0.1%, 0.2% and 0.2% respectively against the U.S. dollar.

In commodities, Brent crude declined 0.2% to $83.25 a barrel. Gold was up 0.2% to $1,762.70 a troy ounce.

The German 10-year bund yield fell to minus 0.092% and U.K. 10-year gilts yields were down to 1.148%. The yield on 10-year U.S. Treasury gained to 1.589% from 1.579%. Yields move inversely to prices.

In Asia, indexes were mixed. Japan's Nikkei 225 index was down 0.3% and China's benchmark Shanghai Composite climbed 0.4% after falling as much as 0.9% earlier.
